                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d14">
                <note rend="inline" type="source">810.20 Defense/1083: Telegram</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">The Ambassador in Colombia</hi> (<persName type="from">
                        <hi rend="italic">Braden</hi>
                    </persName>) <hi rend="italic">to the <gloss type="to">Secretary of
                            State</gloss>
                    </hi>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Bogotá</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1941-07-15T22:00:00-05:00"
                            >July 15, 1941—10 p.m.</date>
                        <lb/>[Received July 16—4:25 a.m.]</dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>269. For Under Secretary. My telegram number 244, July 1 [<hi rend="italic"
                        >2</hi>]. Having sensed diminishment in sympathy for the Nazis in their <pb
                        facs="0024" n="16" xml:id="pg_16"/> war against Russia, today at luncheon I
                    renewed the subject with Minister of War who agreed with me and attributed this
                    favorable development to the Pope’s failure to support Germany and to Russian
                    successes. Nevertheless he still maintained that much of this feeling persisted
                    and would revive strongly were the Nazis to have a rapid and overwhelming
                    victory.</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <hi rend="smallcaps">Braden</hi>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
    </text>
